# UI / Styling Rules

When making any CSS or styling changes:
- Use design system tokens from styles.css (:root block) instead of hardcoded values
- Color tokens: use --color-* variables from `:root` (--color-gold, --color-red, --color-success, --color-surface-1/2/3, --color-text-muted), never hardcode hex values
- Spacing: use --space-* variables or multiples of 8px
- Typography: use --text-* variables for font-size
- Border radius: use --radius-* variables
- Buttons: extend .btn-primary, .btn-secondary, .btn-ghost, or .btn-destructive

When adding new UI components:
- Check if a similar pattern already exists before creating a new class
- Use the existing modal-header, modal-title patterns for dialogs
- Document any new design tokens added to :root

# Scope
These rules apply to all files including src/pages/AdminPage.tsx and styles.css admin-* classes.

# Documentation Rules
After every feature change, new API route, new component, new collection, or infrastructure change:
- Update README.md to reflect the change (features list, setup instructions, environment variables)
- Update system-design.md to reflect the change (services table, architecture, data model, API routes, gaps)
- Update docs/environment.md if any environment variables were added, removed, or changed
- Update .env.example if any environment variables were added or removed
- If a new Firestore composite index is created via the Firebase console, export it with firebase firestore:indexes > firestore.indexes.json and commit the updated file

Do not mark a task as complete without updating documentation.

# Testing Rules
- When adding a new pure utility function in src/lib/, add corresponding Vitest tests in src/lib/*.test.ts
- When fixing a bug in an existing tested function, add a test case that covers the bug
- When adding a new data transformation function in src/data/, add corresponding tests
- Do not add tests for React components, API functions, or Firestore helpers — these are tested manually
- Run npm run test:run after any change to tested files and confirm all tests pass
- Do not break existing tests

# MCP / Firestore
- Firestore MCP is available when vercel dev is not running on port 3000
- To use Firestore MCP: stop vercel dev first, then restart Cursor
- MCP gives Cursor direct read/write access to Firestore for debugging